[src:lerna-monorepo/introduction] Lerna is the original monorepo tool for JavaScript/TypeScript.
[src:lerna-monorepo/introduction] It has been around for many years and has been used by tens of thousands of projects, including React and Jest.
[src:lerna-monorepo/introduction] Nx (the company behind the open source build system of the same name) has taken over stewardship of Lerna.
[src:lerna-monorepo/introduction] Nx is a build system developed by ex-Googlers and utilizes many of the techniques used by internal Google tools.
[src:lerna-monorepo/introduction] Lerna v5 was the first release under this new stewardship, updating outdated packages and starting to do some cleanup on the repository itself.
[src:lerna-monorepo/introduction] Starting with v6+, Lerna delegates task scheduling work to Nx's battle tested, industry-leading task runner, meaning `lerna run` gets the benefits of caching and command distribution for free!
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] In version-control systems, a **monorepo** or **monorepository** ("mono" meaning 'single' and "repo" being short for 'repository') is a software-development strategy in which the code for a number of projects is stored in the same repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] This practice dates back to at least the early 2000s, when it was commonly called a shared codebase.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Google, Meta, Microsoft, Uber, Airbnb, and Twitter all employ very large monorepos with varying strategies to scale build systems and version control software with a large volume of code and daily changes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] A related concept is a monolithic application, but whereas a monolith combines its sub-projects into one large project, a monorepo may contain multiple independent projects.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] In a multiple repository environment where multiple projects depend on a third-party dependency, that dependency might be downloaded or built multiple times.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] In a monorepo the build can be easily optimized, as referenced dependencies all exist in the same codebase.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] When projects that work together are contained in separate repositories, releases need to sync which versions of one project work with the other.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] In a monorepo this problem can be negated, since developers may change multiple projects atomically.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Since developers have access to the entire project, refactors can ensure that every piece of the project continues to function after a refactor.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] teams can improve projects being worked on by other teams.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Although not required, some monorepo builds use one version number across all projects in the repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] With split repositories, access to a repository can be granted based upon need.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] A monorepo allows read access to all software in the project, possibly presenting new security issues.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Note that there are versioning systems in which this limitation is not an issue.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] is used, it's possible to download any part of the repo (even a single directory), and path-based authorization can be used to restrict access to certain parts of a repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] With split repositories, you fetch only the project you are interested in by default.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] This can take up a significant amount of storage space.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] doing so defeats some of the advantages of a monorepo.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Companies with large projects have come across hurdles with monorepos, specifically concerning build tools and version control systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Google's monorepo, speculated to be the largest in the world, meets the classification of an ultra-large-scale system and must handle tens of thousands of contributions every day in a repository over 80 terabytes in size.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Companies using or switching to existing version control software found that software could not efficiently handle the amount of data required for a large monorepo.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Facebook and Microsoft chose to contribute to or fork existing version control software Mercurial and Git respectively, while Google eventually created their own version control system.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] For more than ten years, Google had relied on Perforce hosted on a single machine.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] In 2005 Google's build servers could get locked up to 10 minutes at a time.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Google improved this to 30 seconds–1 minute in 2010.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Due to scaling issues, Google eventually developed its own in-house distributed version control system dubbed Piper.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Facebook ran into performance issues with the version control system Mercurial and made upstream contributions to the client, and in January 2014 made it faster than a competing solution in Git.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] In May 2017 Microsoft announced that virtually all of its Windows engineers use a Git monorepo.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] In the transition, Microsoft made substantial upstream contributions to the Git client to remove unnecessary file access and improve handling of large files with Virtual File System for Git.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Few build tools work well in a monorepo, and flows where builds and continuous integration testing of the entire repository are performed upon check-in will cause performance problems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] A build system that processes dependencies as a directed graph (such as Buck, Bazel, Please, or Pants) solves this by compartmentalizing each build or test to the active area of development.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Twitter began development of Pants in 2011, as both Facebook's Buck and Google's Bazel were closed-source at the time.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Twitter open-sourced Pants in 2012 under the Apache 2.0 License.
[src:lerna-monorepo/monorepo] Please is a Go-based build system; it was developed in 2016 by Thought Machine, whose developers were both inspired by Google's Bazel and dissatisfied with Facebook's Buck.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js allows developers to use JavaScript for writing command line tools and server-side scripting.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Running Javascript on the server is commonly used to generate dynamic web page content before the page is sent to the user's web browser.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Consequently, Node.js represents a "JavaScript everywhere" paradigm, unifying web-application development around a single programming language, as opposed to using different languages for the server- versus client-side programming.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js has an event-driven architecture capable of asynchronous I/O.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] These design choices aim to optimize throughput and scalability in web applications with many input/output operations, as well as for real-time Web applications (e.g., real-time communication programs and browser games).
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The Node.js distributed development project was previously governed by the Node.js Foundation, and has now merged with the JS Foundation to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] OpenJS Foundation is facilitated by the Linux Foundation's Collaborative Projects program.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js was initially written by Ryan Dahl in 2009, about 13 years after the introduction of the first server-side JavaScript environment, Netscape's LiveWire Pro Web.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The initial release supported only Linux and Mac OS X.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Its development and maintenance was led by Dahl and later sponsored by Joyent.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Dahl demonstrated the project at the inaugural European JSConf on November 8, 2009.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js combined Google's V8 JavaScript engine, an event loop, and a low-level I/O API.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In January 2010, a package manager was introduced for the Node.js environment called npm.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The package manager allows programmers to publish and share Node.js packages, along with the accompanying source code, and is designed to simplify the installation, update and uninstallation of packages.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In June 2011, Microsoft and Joyent implemented a native Windows version of Node.js.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The first Node.js build supporting Windows was released in July 2011.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In January 2012, Dahl yielded management of the project to npm creator Isaac Schlueter.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In January 2014, Schlueter announced that Timothy J.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In December 2014, Fedor Indutny created io.js, a fork of Node.js created because of dissatisfaction with Joyent's governance as an open-governance alternative with a separate technical committee.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The goal was to enable a structure that would be more receptive to community input, including the updating of io.js with the latest Google V8 JavaScript engine releases, diverging from Node.js's approach at that time.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The Node.js Foundation, formed to reconcile Node.js and io.js under a unified banner, was announced in February 2015.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The merger was realized in September 2015 with Node.js v0.12 and io.js v3.3 combining into Node v4.0.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] This merge brought V8 ES6 features into Node.js and started a long-term support release cycle.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] By 2016, the io.js website recommended returning to Node.js and announced no further io.js releases, effectively ending the fork and solidifying the merger's success.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In 2019, the JS Foundation and Node.js Foundation merged to form the OpenJS Foundation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The Node.js logo features a green hexagon with overlapping bands to represent the cross-platform nature of the runtime.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The Rocket Turtle was chosen as the official Node.js mascot in February 2024 following a design contest.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js allows the creation of web servers and networking tools using JavaScript and a collection of "modules" that handle various core functionalities.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Modules are provided for file system I/O, networking (DNS, HTTP, TCP, TLS/SSL or UDP), binary data (buffers), cryptography functions, data streams and other core functions.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js's modules use an API designed to reduce the complexity of writing server applications.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Since version 22.6.0, Node.js natively supports both JavaScript and TypeScript, allowing TypeScript files to be executed without a separate compilation step.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The TypeScript support was contributed by Node.js TSC member Marco Ippolito.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In addition, many compile-to-JS languages are available, allowing Node.js applications to also be written in CoffeeScript, Dart, ClojureScript, and others.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js is primarily used to build network programs such as web servers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The most significant difference between Node.js and PHP is that most functions in PHP block until completion (commands execute only after previous commands finish), while Node.js functions are non-blocking (commands execute concurrently and use callbacks to signal completion or failure).
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js is officially supported by Linux, macOS and Microsoft Windows 8.1 and Server 2012 (and later), with Tier 2 support for SmartOS and IBM AIX and experimental support for FreeBSD.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] OpenBSD also works, and LTS versions are available for IBM i (AS/400).
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The source code may also be built on similar operating systems that are not officially supported, such as NonStop OS and Unix servers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js enables development of fast web servers in JavaScript using event-driven programming.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Developers can create scalable servers without using threading by using a simplified model that uses callbacks to signal the completion of a task.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js connects the ease of a scripting language (JavaScript) with the power of Unix network programming.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js was built on top of Google's V8 JavaScript engine since it was open-sourced under the BSD license, and it contains comprehensive support for fundamental protocols such as HTTP, DNS and TCP.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] JavaScript's existing popularity made Node.js accessible to the web-development community.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] There are thousands of open-source libraries for Node.js, most of which are hosted on the npm website.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Multiple developer conferences and events are held that support the Node.js community, including NodeConf, Node Interactive, and Node Summit, as well as a number of regional events.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The open-source community has developed web frameworks to accelerate the development of applications.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Such frameworks include Express.js, Socket.IO, Sails.js, Next.js and Meteor.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Various packages have also been created for interfacing with other languages or runtime environments such as Microsoft .NET.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Modern desktop IDEs provide editing and debugging features specifically for Node.js applications.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Such IDEs include Atom, Brackets, JetBrains WebStorm, Microsoft Visual Studio (with Node.js Tools for Visual Studio, or TypeScript with Node definitions), NetBeans, Nodeclipse Enide Studio (Eclipse-based) and Visual Studio Code.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Some online IDEs also support Node.js, such as Codeanywhere, Eclipse Che, Cloud9 IDE and the visual flow editor in Node-RED.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js is supported across a number of cloud-hosting platforms such as Jelastic, Google Cloud Platform, AWS Elastic Beanstalk, Azure Web Apps and Joyent.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] New major releases of Node.js are cut from the GitHub main branch every six months.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Even-numbered versions are cut in April and odd-numbered versions are cut in October.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] When a new odd version is released, the previous even version undergoes transition to Long Term Support (LTS), which gives that version 12 months of active support from the date it is designated LTS.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] After these 12 months expire, an LTS release receives an additional 18 months of maintenance support.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] An active version receives non-breaking backports of changes a few weeks after they land in the current release.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] A maintenance release receives only critical fixes and documentation updates.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The LTS Working Group manages strategy and policy in collaboration with the Technical Steering Committee of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js is a JavaScript runtime environment that processes incoming requests in a loop, called the event loop.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js uses libuv under the hood to handle asynchronous events.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Libuv is an abstraction layer for network and file system functionality on both Windows and POSIX-based systems such as Linux, macOS, OSS on NonStop, and Unix.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js relies on nghttp2 for HTTP support.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] As of version 20, Node.js uses the ada library which provides up-to-date WHATWG URL compliance.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] As of version 19.5, Node.js uses the simdutf library for fast Unicode validation and transcoding.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] As of version 21.3, Node.js uses the simdjson library for fast JSON parsing.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js operates on a single-thread event loop, using non-blocking I/O calls, allowing it to support tens of thousands of concurrent connections without incurring the cost of thread context switching.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The design of sharing a single thread among all the requests that use the observer pattern is intended for building highly concurrent applications, where any function performing I/O must use a callback.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] To accommodate the single-threaded event loop, Node.js uses the libuv library—which, in turn, uses a fixed-sized thread pool that handles some of the non-blocking asynchronous I/O operations.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] A thread pool handles the execution of parallel tasks in Node.js.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The main thread function call posts tasks to the shared task queue, which threads in the thread pool pull and execute.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Inherently non-blocking system functions such as networking translate to kernel-side non-blocking sockets, while inherently blocking system functions such as file I/O run in a blocking way on their own threads.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] When a thread in the thread pool completes a task, it informs the main thread of this, which in turn, wakes up and executes the registered callback.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] A downside of this single-threaded approach is that Node.js does not allow vertical scaling by increasing the number of CPU cores of the machine it is running on without using an additional module, such as cluster, StrongLoop Process Manager, or pm2.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] However, developers can increase the default number of threads in the libuv thread pool.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The server operating system (OS) is likely to distribute these threads across multiple cores.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Another problem is that long-lasting computations and other CPU-bound tasks freeze the entire event-loop until completion.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] V8 is the JavaScript execution engine which was initially built for Google Chrome.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] It was then open-sourced by Google in 2008.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Written in C++, V8 compiles JavaScript source code to native machine code at runtime.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] As of 2016, it also includes Ignition, a bytecode interpreter.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] npm is the pre-installed package manager for the Node.js server platform.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] It installs Node.js programs from the npm registry, organizing the installation and management of third-party Node.js programs.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js registers with the operating system so the OS notifies it of asynchronous I/O events such as new connections.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Within the Node.js runtime, events trigger callbacks and each connection is handled as a small heap allocation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Traditionally, relatively heavyweight OS processes or threads handled each connection.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js uses an event loop for concurrent I/O, instead of processes or threads.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In contrast to other event-driven servers, Node.js's event loop does not need to be called explicitly.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Instead, callbacks are defined, and the server automatically enters the event loop at the end of the callback definition.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js exits the event loop when there are no further callbacks to be performed.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js supports WebAssembly and as of Node 14 has experimental support of WASI, the WebAssembly System Interface.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Node.js provides a way to create "add-ons" via a C-based API called N-API, which can be used to produce loadable (importable) `.node` modules from source code written in C/C++.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The modules can be directly loaded into memory and executed from within JS environment as simple CommonJS modules.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The implementation of the N-API relies on internal C/C++ Node.js and V8 objects requiring users to import (#include) Node.js specific headers into their native source code.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] As the Node.js API is subject to breaking changes at a binary level, modules have to be built and shipped against specific Node.js versions to work properly.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] To address the issue, third parties have introduced open-sourced С/С++ wrappers on top of the API that partially alleviate the problem.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] They simplify interfaces, but as a side effect they may also introduce complexity which maintainers have to deal with.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Even though the core functionality of Node.js resides in a JavaScript built-in library, modules written in C++ can be used to enhance capabilities and to improve performance of applications.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In order to produce such modules one needs to have an appropriate C++ compiler and necessary headers (the latter are typically shipped with Node.js itself), e.g., gcc, clang or MSVC++.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The N-API is similar to Java Native Interface.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] OpenHarmony and ArkTS also adopts N-API, with the internal implementation rewritten.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In 2015, various branches of the greater Node.js community began working under the vendor-neutral Node.js Foundation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The Node.js Foundation Technical Steering Committee (TSC) is the technical governing body of the Node.js Foundation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The TSC is responsible for the core Node.js repo as well as dependent and adjacent projects.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Generally the TSC delegates the administration of these projects to working groups or committees.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] The LTS group that manages long term supported releases is one such group.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] Other current groups include Website, Streams, Build, Diagnostics, i18n, Evangelism, Docker, Addon API, Benchmarking, Post-mortem, Intl, Documentation, and Testing.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] In August 2017, a third of the TSC members resigned due to a dispute related to the project's code of conduct.
[src:lerna-monorepo/node-js] They resigned after a vote failed to remove a member from the leadership group against whom multiple complaints had been filed.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] A **package manager**, or **package management system**, is software that supports installing, upgrading, configuring, and removing software for the host system in a consistent manner.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] A package manager deals with *packages*, distributions of software and data in archive files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Packages contain metadata, such as the software's name, description of its purpose, version number, vendor, checksum (usually a cryptographic hash function), and a list of dependencies necessary for the software to run properly.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Upon installation, metadata is stored in a local package database.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Package managers typically maintain a database of software dependencies and version information to prevent software mismatches and missing prerequisites.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] They work closely with software repositories, binary repository managers, and app stores.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Package managers are designed to eliminate the need for manual installs and updates.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] This can be particularly useful for large enterprises whose operating systems (OSes) typically consist of hundreds or even tens of thousands of distinct packages.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] An early package manager was SMIT (and its backend install) from IBM AIX.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] SMIT was introduced with AIX 3.0 in 1989.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Package managers like dpkg have existed as early as 1994.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Early package managers, from around 1994, had no automatic dependency resolution but could already simplify the process of adding and removing software from a running system.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] By around 1995, beginning with CPAN, package managers began handling package repository downloads, and dependency resolution and installation as needed, making it easier to install, uninstall and update software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] A software package is an archive file containing a computer program as well as necessary metadata for its deployment.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] The program may be in source code that has to be compiled and built first.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Package metadata include the software's description, version number, and dependencies.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Package managers are charged with the task of finding, installing, maintaining or uninstalling packages upon the user's command.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Computer systems that rely on dynamic library linking, instead of static library linking, share executable libraries of machine instructions across packages and applications.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] In these systems, conflicting relationships between different packages requiring different versions of libraries results in a situation called *dependency hell*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] On Microsoft Windows systems, this is also called *DLL hell* when working with dynamically-linked libraries.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Modern package managers have mostly solved these problems by allowing parallel installation of multiple library versions (e.g.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] OPENSTEP's *Framework* system), a dependency of any kind (e.g.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] *slots* in Gentoo Portage), and even packages compiled with different compiler versions (e.g. dynamic libraries built by the Glasgow Haskell Compiler, where a stable ABI does not exist), in order to enable other packages to specify which version they are linked or installed against.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] System administrators may install and maintain software using tools other than package managers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] For example, a local administrator may download unpackaged source code, compile it, and install it.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] This may cause the local system to fall out of synchronization with the package manager's database.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] The local administrator will be required to take additional measures, such as manually managing some dependencies or integrating the changes into the package manager.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] There are tools to ensure that locally-compiled packages are integrated with the package management.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Upgrades of configuration files may be particularly troublesome.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Since package managers, at least on Unix systems, originated as extensions of file archivers, they can usually only overwrite or retain configuration files, rather than apply rules to them.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] There are exceptions to this that usually apply to kernel configuration (which, if broken, will render the computer unusable after a restart).
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Problems can be caused if the configuration file format changes; for instance, if the old file does not explicitly disable new options that should be disabled.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Some package managers, such as Debian's dpkg, allow configuration during installation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] In other situations, packages are installed with the default configuration, which is then overwritten, for example in headless installations to a large number of computers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] This kind of pre-configured installation is also supported by dpkg.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] To give users more control over the software they allow to be installed on their systems, and sometimes due to legal or convenience reasons on the distributors' side, packages are often downloaded from software repositories.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Many package managers can be configured to never upgrade certain packages, or to upgrade them only when critical vulnerabilities or instabilities are found in the previous version, as defined by the packager of the software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] This process is called *upgrade suppression*, or *version pinning*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Some of the more advanced package management features offer *cascading package removal*, in which all packages that depend on the target package and all packages that only it depends on are also removed.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Although commands are specific to each package manager, they are translatable to a large extent, as most package managers offer similar functions.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] The Arch Linux wiki offers an extensive overview of commands.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Linux distributions oriented to binary packages rely heavily on package management systems as their primary means of managing and maintaining software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Mobile operating systems such as Android (Linux-based) and iOS (Unix-based) rely almost exclusively on their respective vendors' app stores and thus use their own dedicated package management systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] A package manager is often called an *install manager*, which can lead to a confusion between package managers and installers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Most software configuration management systems treat building software and deploying software as separate, independent steps.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] A build automation utility typically takes human-readable source code files already on a computer, and automates the process of converting them into an executable package on the same or a remote computer.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Later, a package manager typically running on another computer downloads the pre-built executable and installs it.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] A few tools, such as Maak and A-A-P, are designed to handle both building and deployment, and can be used as either build automation utilities, package managers, or both.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] App stores can also be considered application-level package managers (without the ability to install all levels of programs).
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Unlike traditional package managers, app stores are designed to enable payment for the software itself (instead of for software development), and may only offer monolithic packages with no dependencies or dependency resolution.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] They are usually limited in their management functionality, due to focusing on ease-of-use over power or emergence, and are common in commercial operating systems and smart devices.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Package managers also often have only human-reviewed code.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Many app stores, such as Google Play and Apple's App Store, mainly screen apps using automated tools only; malware can pass these tests by detecting when the app is being tested, and delaying malicious activity.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] There are exceptions: the npm package database, for instance, relies entirely on post-publication review of its code, while the Debian package database has an extensive human review process before any package goes into the main database.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] The XZ Utils backdoor used years of trust-building to insert a backdoor, which was nonetheless caught while in the testing database.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Also known as binary repository manager, it is a software tool designed to optimize the download and storage of binary files, artifacts and packages used and produced in the software development process.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] These package managers aim to standardize the way enterprises treat all package types.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] They give users the ability to apply security and compliance metrics across all artifact types.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Universal package managers have been referred to as being at the center of a DevOps toolchain.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Each package manager relies on the format and metadata of the packages in its repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] That is, package managers need groups of files to be bundled along with appropriate metadata, such as dependencies.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Often, a core set of utilities manages the basic installation from these packages and multiple package managers use these utilities to provide additional functionality.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] For example, yum relies on rpm as a backend.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Yum extends the functionality of rpm by adding features such as simple configuration for maintaining a network of systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] As another example, the Synaptic Package Manager provides a graphical user interface by using the Advanced Packaging Tool (apt) library, which in turn relies on dpkg for core functionality.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Alien is a program that converts between different Linux package formats, supporting conversion between Linux Standard Base (LSB) compliant .rpm packages, .deb, Stampede (.slp), Solaris (.pkg) and Slackware (.tgz, .txz, .tbz, .tlz) packages.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] For mobile operating systems, Google Play uses the Android application package (APK) package format while Microsoft Store uses the APPX and XAP formats.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Both Google Play and Microsoft Store have eponymous package managers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] By the nature of free and open-source software (FOSS), packages under similar and compatible licenses are available on a number of operating systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] These packages can be combined and distributed using configurable packaging systems to handle many permutations of software and manage version-specific dependencies and conflicts.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Some managers of FOSS packages are released as FOSS themselves.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] The ability to continuously upgrade third-party software is typically added by adding the URL of the corresponding repository to the package management's configuration file.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Besides system-level application managers, there are add-on package managers for operating systems with limited capabilities and for programming languages in which developers need the latest libraries.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Unlike system-level package managers, application-level package managers focus on a small part of the software system.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] They typically reside within a directory tree that is not maintained by the system-level manager, such as c:\cygwin or /opt/sw.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] This may not be the case for managers that deal with programming libraries, leading to possible conflicts, as both managers may claim to own a file and may break upgrades.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] Ian Murdock commented that package management is "the single biggest advancement Linux has brought to the industry", that it blurs the boundaries between operating systems and applications, and that it makes it "easier to push new innovations [...] into the marketplace and [...] evolve the OS".
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] There is also a conference for package manager developers known as PackagingCon.
[src:lerna-monorepo/package-manager] It was established in 2021 with the aim to understand different approaches to package management.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] A **software repository**, or **repo** for short, is a storage location for software packages.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Often a table of contents is also stored, along with metadata.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] A software repository is typically managed by source or version control, or repository managers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Package managers allow automatically installing and updating repositories, sometimes called "packages".
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Many software publishers and other organizations maintain servers on the Internet for this purpose, either free of charge or for a subscription fee.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Repositories may be solely for particular programs, such as CPAN for the Perl programming language, or for an entire operating system.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Operators of such repositories typically provide a package management system, tools intended to search for, install and otherwise manipulate software packages from the repositories.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] For example, many Linux distributions use Advanced Packaging Tool (APT), commonly found in Debian based distributions, or Yellowdog Updater, Modified (yum) found in Red Hat based distributions.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] There are also multiple independent package management systems, such as pacman, used in Arch Linux and equo, found in Sabayon Linux.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] As software repositories are designed to include useful packages, major repositories are designed to be malware free.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] If a computer is configured to use a digitally signed repository from a reputable vendor, and is coupled with an appropriate permissions system, this significantly reduces the threat of malware to these systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] As a side effect, many systems that have these abilities do not need anti-malware software such as antivirus software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Most major Linux distributions have many repositories around the world that mirror the main repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] At client side, a package manager helps installing from and updating the repositories.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] A package management system is different from a package development process.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] A typical use of a package management system is to facilitate the integration of code from possibly different sources into a coherent stand-alone operating unit.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Thus, a package management system might be used to produce a distribution of Linux, possibly a distribution tailored to a specific restricted application.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] A package development process, by contrast, is used to manage the co-development of code and documentation of a collection of functions or routines with a common theme, producing thereby a package of software functions that typically will not be complete and usable by themselves.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] A good package development process will help users conform to good documentation and coding practices, integrating some level of unit testing.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] The following table lists a few languages with repositories for contributed software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] The "Autochecks" column describes the routine checks done.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Very few people have the ability to test their software under multiple operating systems with different versions of the core code and with other contributed packages they may use.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] For the R programming language, the Comprehensive R Archive Network (CRAN) runs tests routinely.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] To understand how this is valuable, imagine a situation with two developers, Sally and John.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Sally only runs the current version of the software under one version of Microsoft Windows, and has only tested it in that environment.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] At more or less regular intervals, CRAN tests Sally's contribution under a dozen combinations of operating systems and versions of the core R language software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] If one of them generates an error, she gets that error message.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] With luck, that error message details may provide enough input to allow enable a fix for the error, even if she cannot replicate it with her current hardware and software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Next, suppose John contributes to the repository a package B that uses a package A.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Package B passes all the tests and is made available to users.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Later, Sally submits an improved version of A, which breaks B.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] The autochecks make it possible to provide information to John so he can fix the problem.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] This example exposes both a strength and a weakness in the R contributed-package system: CRAN supports this kind of automated testing of contributed packages, but packages contributed to CRAN need not specify the versions of other contributed packages that they use.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Procedures for requesting specific versions of packages exist, but contributors might not use those procedures.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Beyond this, a repository such as CRAN running regular checks of contributed packages actually provides an extensive if *ad hoc* test suite for development versions of the core language.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] If Sally (in the example above) gets an error message she does not understand or thinks is inappropriate, especially from a development version of the language, she can (and often does with R) ask the core development-team for the language for help.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] In this way, the repository can contribute to improving the quality of the core language software.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Package managers help manage repositories and the distribution of them.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] If a repository is updated, a package manager will usually allow a user to update that repository through the manager.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] It also helps to manage things such as dependencies between other repositories.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] In an enterprise environment, a software repository is usually used to store artifacts, or to mirror external repositories which may be inaccessible due to security restrictions.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] One example is Sonatype Nexus Repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] At server side, a software repository is typically managed by source control or repository managers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Some of the repository managers allow to aggregate other repository location into one URL and provide a caching proxy.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] When doing continuous builds many artifacts are produced and often centrally stored, so automatically deleting the ones which are not released is important.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] As part of the development lifecycle, source code is continuously being built into binary artifacts using continuous integration.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] This may interact with a binary repository manager much like a developer would by getting artifacts from the repositories and pushing builds there.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Artifacts and packages inherently mean different things.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Artifacts are simply an output or collection of files (ex.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] JAR, WAR, DLLS, RPM etc.) and one of those files may contain metadata (e.g.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Whereas packages are a single archive file in a well-defined format (ex.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] NuGet) that contain files appropriate for the package type (ex.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Many artifacts result from builds but other types are crucial as well.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Packages are essentially one of two things: a library or an application.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Compared to source files, binary artifacts are often larger by orders of magnitude, they are rarely deleted or overwritten (except for rare cases such as snapshots or nightly builds), and they are usually accompanied by much metadata such as id, package name, version, license and more.
[src:lerna-monorepo/software-repository] Metadata describes a binary artifact, is stored and specified separately from the artifact itself, and can have several additional uses.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Version control is a component of software configuration management.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A **version control system** is a software tool that automates version control.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Alternatively, version control is embedded as a feature of some systems such as word processors, spreadsheets, collaborative web docs, and content management systems, such as Wikipedia's page history.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Version control includes options to view old versions and to revert a file to a previous version.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] As teams develop software, it is common to deploy multiple versions of the same software, and for different developers to work on one or more different versions simultaneously.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Bugs or features of the software are often only present in certain versions (because of the fixing of some problems and the introduction of others as the program develops).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Therefore, for the purposes of locating and fixing bugs, it is vitally important to be able to retrieve and run different versions of the software to determine in which version(s) the problem occurs.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] It may also be necessary to develop two versions of the software concurrently: for instance, where one version has bugs fixed, but no new features (branch), while the other version is where new features are worked on (trunk).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] At the simplest level, developers could simply retain multiple copies of the different versions of the program, and label them appropriately.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This simple approach has been used in many large software projects.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] While this method can work, it is inefficient as many near-identical copies of the program have to be maintained.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This requires a lot of self-discipline on the part of developers and often leads to mistakes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Since the code base is the same, it also requires granting read-write-execute permission to a set of developers, and this adds the pressure of someone managing permissions so that the code base is not compromised, which adds more complexity.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Consequently, systems to automate some or all of the revision control process have been developed.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This abstracts most operational steps (hides them from ordinary users).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Moreover, in software development, legal and business practice, and other environments, it has become increasingly common for a single document or snippet of code to be edited by a team, the members of which may be geographically dispersed and may pursue different and even contrary interests.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Sophisticated revision control that tracks and accounts for ownership of changes to documents and code may be extremely helpful or even indispensable in such situations.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Revision control may also track changes to configuration files, such as those typically stored in `/etc` or `/usr/local/etc` on Unix systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This gives system administrators another way to easily track changes made and a way to roll back to earlier versions should the need arise.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Many version control systems identify the version of a file as a number or letter, called the *version number*, *version*, *revision number*, *revision*, or *revision level*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] For example, the first version of a file might be version *1*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When the file is changed the next version is *2*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Each version is associated with a timestamp and the person making the change.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Revisions can be compared, restored, and, with some types of files, merged.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] IBM's OS/360 IEBUPDTE software update tool dates back to 1962, arguably a precursor to version control system tools.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Two source management and version control packages that were heavily used by IBM 360/370 installations were The Librarian and Panvalet.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A full system designed for source code control was started in 1972: the Source Code Control System (SCCS), again for the OS/360.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] SCCS's user manual, especially the introduction, which was published on December 4, 1975, implied that it was the first deliberate revision control system.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The Revision Control System (RCS) followed in 1982 and, later, Concurrent Versions System (CVS) added network and concurrent development features to RCS.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] After CVS, a dominant successor was Subversion, followed by the rise of distributed version control tools such as Git.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Revision control manages changes to a set of data over time.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] These changes can be structured in various ways.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Often the data is thought of as a collection of many individual items, such as files or documents, and changes to individual files are tracked.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This is in line with the notion of keeping files separate but causes problems when identity changes, which happens when files are renamed, split or merged.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Accordingly, some systems such as Git, consider changes to the data as a whole instead, which is less intuitive for simple changes but simplifies more complex changes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] As a simple example, when editing a computer file, the data stored in memory by the editing program is the working copy, which is committed by saving the file.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Concretely, one may print out a document, edit it by hand, and only later manually input the changes into a computer and save it.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] For source code control, the working copy is instead a copy of all files in a particular revision, generally stored locally on the developer's computer; in this case saving the file only changes the working copy, and checking into the repository is a separate step.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] If multiple people are working on a single data set or document, they are implicitly creating branches of the data (in their working copies), and thus issues of merging arise, as discussed below.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] For simple collaborative document editing, this can be prevented by using file locking or simply avoiding working on the same document that someone else is working on.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Revision control systems are often centralized, with a single authoritative data store, the *repository,* and check-outs and check-ins done with reference to this central repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Alternatively, in distributed revision control, no single repository is authoritative, and data can be checked out and checked into any repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When checking into a different repository, this is interpreted as a merge or patch.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In terms of graph theory, revisions are generally thought of as a line of development (the *trunk*) with branches off of this, forming a directed tree, visualized as one or more parallel lines of development (the "mainlines" of the branches) branching off a trunk.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In reality the structure is more complicated, forming a directed acyclic graph, but for many purposes "tree with merges" is an adequate approximation.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Revisions occur in sequence over time, and thus can be arranged in order, either by revision number or timestamp.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Revisions are based on past revisions, though it is possible to largely or completely replace an earlier revision, such as "delete all existing text, insert new text".
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In the simplest case, with no branching or undoing, each revision is based on its immediate predecessor alone, and they form a simple line, with a single latest version, the "HEAD" revision or *tip*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In graph theory terms, drawing each revision as a point and each "derived revision" relationship as an arrow (conventionally pointing from older to newer, in the same direction as time), this is a linear graph.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In principle the resulting tree need not have a preferred tip ("main" latest revision) – just various different revisions – but in practice one tip is generally identified as HEAD.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When a new revision is based on HEAD, it is either identified as the new HEAD, or considered a new branch.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This most often occurs when changes occur in multiple branches (most often two, but more are possible), which are then merged into a single branch incorporating both changes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] If these changes overlap, it may be difficult or impossible to merge, and require manual intervention or rewriting.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In the presence of merges, the resulting graph is no longer a tree, as nodes can have multiple parents, but is instead a rooted directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The graph is acyclic since parents are always backwards in time, and rooted because there is an oldest version.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Assuming there is a trunk, merges from branches can be considered as "external" to the tree – the changes in the branch are packaged up as a *patch,* which is applied to HEAD (of the trunk), creating a new revision without any explicit reference to the branch, and preserving the tree structure.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Thus, while the actual relations between versions form a DAG, this can be considered a tree plus merges, and the trunk itself is a line.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In distributed revision control, in the presence of multiple repositories these may be based on a single original version (a root of the tree), but there need not be an original root - instead there can be a separate root (oldest revision) for each repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This can happen, for example, if two people start working on a project separately.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Similarly, in the presence of multiple data sets (multiple projects) that exchange data or merge, there is no single root, though for simplicity one may think of one project as primary and the other as secondary, merged into the first with or without its own revision history.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Engineering revision control developed from formalized processes based on tracking revisions of early blueprints or bluelines*"MIL-STD-100G: Department of Defense Standard Practice for Engineering Drawings" (PDF).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This system of control implicitly allowed returning to an earlier state of the design, for cases in which an engineering dead-end was reached in the development of the design.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A revision table was used to keep track of the changes made.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Additionally, the modified areas of the drawing were highlighted using revision clouds.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Version control is widespread in business and law.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Indeed, "contract redline" and "legal blackline" are some of the earliest forms of revision control, and are still employed in business and law with varying degrees of sophistication.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The most sophisticated techniques are beginning to be used for the electronic tracking of changes to CAD files (see product data management), supplanting the "manual" electronic implementation of traditional revision control.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Game development often involves large binary files and teams working together across different disciplines.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] As a result, game studios use version control systems with good support for large binary files, file locking, and fast synchronization.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Common tools include Perforce and several newer cloud-based systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Traditional revision control systems use a centralized model where all the revision control functions take place on a shared server.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] If two developers try to change the same file at the same time, without some method of managing access the developers may end up overwriting each other's work.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Centralized revision control systems solve this problem in one of two different "source management models": file locking and version merging.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] An operation is *atomic* if the system is left in a consistent state even if the operation is interrupted.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The *commit* operation is usually the most critical in this sense.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Commits tell the revision control system to make a group of changes final, and available to all users.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Not all revision control systems have atomic commits; Concurrent Versions System lacks this feature.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The simplest method of preventing "concurrent access" problems involves locking files so that only one developer at a time has write access to the central "repository" copies of those files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Once one developer "checks out" a file, others can read that file, but no one else may change that file until that developer "checks in" the updated version (or cancels the checkout).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] File locking has both merits and drawbacks.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] It can provide some protection against difficult merge conflicts when a user is making radical changes to many sections of a large file (or group of files).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] If the files are left exclusively locked for too long, other developers may be tempted to bypass the revision control software and change the files locally, forcing a difficult manual merge when the other changes are finally checked in.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In a large organization, files can be left "checked out" and locked and forgotten about as developers move between projects - these tools may or may not make it easy to see who has a file checked out.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Most version control systems allow multiple developers to edit the same file at the same time.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The first developer to "check in" changes to the central repository always succeeds.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The system may provide facilities to merge further changes into the central repository, and preserve the changes from the first developer when other developers check in.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Merging two files can be a very delicate operation, and usually possible only if the data structure is simple, as in text files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The result of a merge of two image files might not result in an image file at all.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The second developer checking in files will need to take care with the merge, to make sure that the changes are compatible and that the merge operation does not introduce its own logic errors within the files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] These problems limit the availability of automatic or semi-automatic merge operations mainly to simple text-based documents, unless a specific merge plugin is available for the file types.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The concept of a *reserved edit* can provide an optional means to explicitly lock a file for exclusive write access, even when a merging capability exists.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Most revision control tools will use only one of these similar terms (baseline, label, tag) to refer to the action of identifying a snapshot ("label the project") or the record of the snapshot ("try it with baseline *X*").
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Typically only one of the terms *baseline*, *label*, or *tag* is used in documentation or discussion ; they can be considered synonyms.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In most projects, some snapshots are more significant than others, such as those used to indicate published releases, branches, or milestones.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When both the term *baseline* and either of *label* or *tag* are used together in the same context, *label* and *tag* usually refer to the mechanism within the tool of identifying or making the record of the snapshot, and *baseline* indicates the increased significance of any given label or tag.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Most formal discussion of configuration management uses the term *baseline*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Distributed revision control systems (DRCS) take a peer-to-peer approach, as opposed to the client–server approach of centralized systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Rather than a single, central repository on which clients synchronize, each peer's working copy of the codebase is a bona-fide repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Distributed revision control conducts synchronization by exchanging patches (change-sets) from peer to peer.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Rather, communication is only necessary when pushing or pulling changes to or from other peers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Following best practices is necessary to obtain the full benefits of version control.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Best practice may vary by version control tool and the field to which version control is applied.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Other software development best practices such as code review and automated regression testing may assist in the following of version control best practices.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Costs and benefits will vary dependent upon the version control tool chosen and the field in which it is applied.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This section speaks to the field of software development, where version control is widely applied.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In addition to the costs of licensing the version control software, using version control requires time and effort.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The concepts underlying version control must be understood and the technical particulars required to operate the version control software chosen must be learned.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Version control best practices must be learned and integrated into the organization's existing software development practices.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Management effort may be required to maintain the discipline needed to follow best practices in order to obtain useful benefit.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A core benefit is the ability to keep history and revert changes, allowing the developer to easily undo changes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This gives the developer more opportunity to experiment, eliminating the fear of breaking existing code.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Branching assists with deployment and release management.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] There can be damage mitigation, accountability, process and design improvement, and other benefits associated with the record keeping provided by version control, the tracking of who did what, when, why, and how.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When bugs arise, knowing what was done when helps with damage mitigation and recovery by assisting in the identification of what problems exist, how long they have existed, and determining problem scope and solutions.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Previous versions can be installed and tested to verify conclusions reached by examination of code and commit messages.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Version control can greatly simplify debugging.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The application of a test case to multiple versions can quickly identify the change which introduced a bug.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The developer need not be familiar with the entire code base and can focus instead on the code that introduced the problem.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Version control enhances collaboration in multiple ways.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Since version control can identify conflicting changes, i.e. incompatible changes made to the same lines of code, there is less need for coordination among developers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The packaging of commits, branches, and all the associated commit messages and version labels, improves communication between developers, both in the moment and over time.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Better communication, whether instant or deferred, can improve the code review process, the testing process, and other critical aspects of the software development process.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Some of the more advanced revision-control tools offer many other facilities, allowing deeper integration with other tools and software-engineering processes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Plugins are often available for IDEs such as Oracle JDeveloper, IntelliJ IDEA, Eclipse, Visual Studio, Delphi, NetBeans IDE, Xcode, and GNU Emacs (via vc.el).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Advanced research prototypes generate appropriate commit messages.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] An approved revision of a document or source file to which subsequent changes can be made.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A search for the author and revision that last modified a particular line.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A set of files under version control may be *branched* or *forked* at a point in time so that, from that time forward, two copies of those files may develop at different speeds or in different ways independently of each other.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A *change* (or *diff*, or *delta*) represents a specific modification to a document under version control.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The granularity of the modification considered a change varies between version control systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] On many version control systems with atomic multi-change commits, a *change list* (or *CL*), *change set*, *update*, or *patch* identifies the set of *changes* made in a single commit.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This can also represent a sequential view of the source code, allowing the examination of source as of any particular changelist ID.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] To *check out* (or *co*) is to create a local working copy from the repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A user may specify a specific revision or obtain the latest.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The term 'checkout' can also be used as a noun to describe the working copy.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When a file has been checked out from a shared file server, it cannot be edited by other users.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Think of it like a hotel, when you check out, you no longer have access to its amenities.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In version control software, a changeset (also known as commit and revision) is a set of alterations packaged together, along with meta-information about the alterations.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A changeset describes the exact differences between two successive versions in the version control system's repository of changes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Changesets are typically treated as an atomic unit, an indivisible set, by version control systems.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] To *commit* (*check in*, *ci* or, more rarely, *install*, *submit* or *record*) is to write or merge the changes made in the working copy back to the repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A commit contains metadata, typically the author information and a commit message that describes the change.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A short note, written by the developer, stored with the commit, which describes the commit.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Ideally, it records why the modification was made, a description of the modification's effect or purpose, and non-obvious aspects of how the change works.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A conflict occurs when different parties make changes to the same document, and the system is unable to reconcile the changes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A user must *resolve* the conflict by combining the changes, or by selecting one change in favour of the other.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Most revision control software uses delta compression, which retains only the differences between successive versions of files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This allows for more efficient storage of many different versions of files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A stream in which some or all file versions are mirrors of the parent stream's versions.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The process of merging changes made in the main *trunk* into a development (feature or team) branch.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Also sometimes called *tip*, this refers to the most recent commit, either to the trunk or to a branch.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The trunk and each branch have their own head, though HEAD is sometimes loosely used to refer to the trunk.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Some revision control software uses Interleaved deltas, a method that allows storing the history of text based files in a more efficient way than by using Delta compression.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When a developer *locks* a file, no one else can update that file until it is unlocked.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Locking can be supported by the version control system, or via informal communications between developers (aka *social locking*).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Similar to *trunk*, but there can be a mainline for each branch.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A *merge* or *integration* is an operation in which two sets of changes are applied to a file or set of files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The act of copying file content from a less controlled location into a more controlled location.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] For example, from a user's workspace into a repository, or from a stream to its parent.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Copy revisions from one repository into another.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] *Pull* is initiated by the receiving repository, while *push* is initiated by the source.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] *Fetch* is sometimes used as a synonym for *pull*, or to mean a *pull* followed by an *update*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Contributions to a source code repository that uses a distributed version control system are commonly made by means of a pull request, also known as a merge request.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The contributor requests that the project maintainer *pull* the source code change, hence the name "pull request".
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The maintainer has to *merge* the pull request if the contribution should become part of the source base.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The developer creates a pull request to notify maintainers of a new change; a comment thread is associated with each pull request.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] This allows for focused discussion of code changes.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Submitted pull requests are visible to anyone with repository access.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A pull request can be accepted or rejected by maintainers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Once the pull request is reviewed and approved, it is merged into the repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Depending on the established workflow, the code may need to be tested before being included into official release.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Therefore, some projects contain a special branch for merging untested pull requests.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Other projects run an automated test suite on every pull request, using a continuous integration tool, and the reviewer checks that any new code has appropriate test coverage.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In version control systems, a repository is a data structure that stores metadata for a set of files or directory structure.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Depending on whether the version control system in use is distributed, like Git or Mercurial, or centralized, like Subversion, CVS, or Perforce, the whole set of information in the repository may be duplicated on every user's system or may be maintained on a single server.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Some of the metadata that a repository contains includes, among other things, a historical record of changes in the repository, a set of commit objects, and a set of references to commit objects, called *heads*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The act of user intervention to address a conflict between different changes to the same document.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The process of merging different team branches into the main trunk of the versioning system.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] In SVK, a Revision is the state at a point in time of the entire tree in the repository.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The act of making one file or folder available in multiple branches at the same time.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] When a shared file is changed in one branch, it is changed in other branches.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A container for branched files that has a known relationship to other such containers.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] Streams form a hierarchy; each stream can inherit various properties (like versions, namespace, workflow rules, subscribers, etc.) from its parent stream.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] A *tag* or *label* refers to an important snapshot in time, consistent across many files.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] These files at that point may all be tagged with a user-friendly, meaningful name or revision number.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] An *update* (or *sync*, but *sync* can also mean a combined *push* and *pull*) merges changes made in the repository (by other people, for example) into the local *working copy*.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] *Update* is also the term used by some CM tools (CM+, PLS, SMS) for the change package concept (see *changelist*).
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] The *working copy* is the local copy of files from a repository, at a specific time or revision.
[src:lerna-monorepo/version-control] All work done to the files in a repository is initially done on a working copy, hence the name.
